About

This is an R guide to work with the 2018-2019 National Health Survey of Ecuador. If you want to know more about this survey, go to https://www.ecuadorencifras.gob.ec/salud-salud-reproductiva-y-nutricion/

All the files are open access and can be downloaded here. However, I re-uploaded them to OSF to import them with R Studio:

Required packages

install.packages("osfr")
install.packages("fabricatr")
options("scipen" = 20)

Importing the datasets

library(osfr)
ENSANUT_EC <- osf_retrieve_node("https://osf.io/e3pgz/") 
ENSANUT_DIRECTORY  <- osf_ls_files(ENSANUT_EC)
ENSANUT_DIRECTORY ## See files

osf_download(ENSANUT_DIRECTORY, path = getwd(), conflicts = "overwrite", progress = T) ## Downloading the files to the local directory

Selecting the main dataset (and associated variables).

The dataset selection must be based on your unit of analysis. My unit of analysis is children under 5, hence I will work with âDevelopmentâ as my main data frame.

MyData <- Merged03

Renaming, recoding, and creating derived variables

Now that you have all the information you need in a single dataset, you can start coding your variables following the OSF registration template. Let us talk about:

Exposure

Mistimed or unintended pregnancy is measured using the âf2_s4a_403_â variable, which asked women âwhen you got pregnant, you wanted toâ¦?
* have that kid * wait more time * not have more kids * not have [my first] kid.

We transformed this into a binary variable with the first option coded as 0 and the other options coded as 1.

MyData$f2_s4a_403_ <- as.factor(MyData$f2_s4a_403_)
summary(MyData$f2_s4a_403_[MyData$f5_s5_500 %in% "niÃ±os/as de 3 a menores de 5 aÃ±os"]) #I am preserving all kids because I need their factors of expansion, but I will present summaries of the target population only
##        no querÃ­a mÃ¡s hijos?      no querÃ­a tener hijos? 
##                         512                         199 
## querÃ­a esperar mas tiempo ?             tener ese hijo? 
##                        1029                        5172 
##                        NA's 
##                         501
MyData$undesired_mom <- ifelse(MyData$f2_s4a_403_ %in% "tener ese hijo?", 0,1)
hist(MyData$undesired_mom[MyData$f5_s5_500 %in% "niÃ±os/as de 3 a menores de 5 aÃ±os"]) # 1 represents unintended or mistimed pregnancy

Outcome

The main outcome is Early Childhood Development derived from four domains. Each domain is composed by a set of tasks the kid should (or should not) perform. Each domain has its own threshold.

DOMAIN Variables Threshold
Language/literacy and numeracy f5_s5_501,f5_s5_502,f5_s5_503 At least two
Physical f5_s5_504, !f5_s5_505 All
Cognitive development f5_s5_506,f5_s5_507 At least one
Social emotional f5_s5_508, !f5_s5_509, !f5_s5_510 At least two

If the kid is proficient in three out of the four domains ("Tier II), we consider he or she has a normal development (coded as 1). Kids who did not meet this criterion were coded as 0.

MyData$f5_s5_501 <- as.factor(MyData$f5_s5_501)
MyData$f5_s5_502 <- as.factor(MyData$f5_s5_502)
MyData$f5_s5_503 <- as.factor(MyData$f5_s5_503)
MyData$f5_s5_504 <- as.factor(MyData$f5_s5_504)

hist(MyData$phy[MyData$f5_s5_500 %in% "niÃ±os/as de 3 a menores de 5 aÃ±os"])

#c. Perform at least one of these (Learning): f5_s5_506,f5_s5_507; and
MyData$lear1 <- ifelse(MyData$f5_s5_506 %in% "si",1,0)
MyData$lear2 <- ifelse(MyData$f5_s5_507 %in% "si",1,0)
MyData$learning <- ifelse(MyData$lear2+MyData$lear1>=1,1,0)
hist(MyData$learning[MyData$f5_s5_500 %in% "niÃ±os/as de 3 a menores de 5 aÃ±os"])

#d. Perform at least two of these (Social_emotional): f5_s5_508, !f5_s5_509, !f5_s5_510
MyData$soc1 <- ifelse(MyData$f5_s5_508 %in% "si",1,0)

hist(MyData$social_emotional[MyData$f5_s5_500 %in% "niÃ±os/as de 3 a menores de 5 aÃ±os"])

MyData$Development_score <- MyData$lit_num+MyData$phy+MyData$learning+MyData$social_emotional
hist(MyData$Development_score[MyData$f5_s5_500 %in% "niÃ±os/as de 3 a menores de 5 aÃ±os"])

MyData$outcome <- ifelse(MyData$Development_score >= 3,1,0)
hist(MyData$outcome[MyData$f5_s5_500 %in% "niÃ±os/as de 3 a menores de 5 aÃ±os"])

Confounders

We stated the assumed relationships between our variables using a directed acyclic graph. Based on these assumptions, we identified a set of covariates required for minimal sufficient adjustment: * Geographic area; * Household income; * Mistimed or unintended pregnancy according to the father; * The motherâs current marital status; * The motherâs current age; * The motherâs ethnicity; * The motherâs educational level; * Whether the mother presentâs functional limitations related to depressive symptoms; * The childâs age; and * The number of months the child has attended a daycare.

Geographic area

The geographic area (âareaâ) is Classified as either urban or rural.

MyData$area <- as.factor(MyData$area)

Household income

Household income was built based on a list of indicators identified by a previous study that aimed to built a wealth index with variables from the Ecuadorian National Health Survey using Principal Component Analysis and classifying their added value in quintires. We used a similar methodology. Access to internet (âf1_s1_42â), tv(âf1_s1_44_7â), fridge(âf1_s1_44_1â), desktop computer(âf1_s1_44_2â), laundry machine(âf1_s1_44_3â), blender(âf1_s1_44_4â), pipeline water(âf1_s1_24â), iron(âf1_s1_44_6â), heat(âf1_s1_44_9â), landline (âf1_s1_44_10â), and dvd player (âf1_s1_44_8â) was coded as 1. Having a roof of concrete/slab/cement/tile/zinc was coded as 1 and roofs with other materials (Asbestos/Palm/straw/leaf/Other) were coded as 0. A similar process was followed for the floor (cement/brick/ceramic/tile/vinyl/stave/parquet/plank/treated plank/floating floor/marble/marmeton as 1 and board/untreated plank/Reed/Earth/Other as 0). Finally, the number of rooms was recoded to 1, 2, or 3 (more than two). We summed these variables and recoded the result by quintiles as a numeric variable (1 to 5).

MyData$f1_s1_42 <- as.factor(MyData$f1_s1_42)

Other covariates

We also identified variables that might add precision to our model, might be potential mediators, or useful for stratified, subgroup, sensitivity, or secondary analysis. These variables included the number of months the child went to daycareâcalculated as 0 for children who had not attended daycare (âf5_s2_200â) and summing the values for years (âf5_s2_204_1â) and months (âf5_s2_204_2â) for all the others, whether or not the child was considered malnourished (âdcronicaâ), whether or not the child attended classes with structured learning (âf5_s5_511â). We also built an alternative exposure variable where either parent felt it was not the right time or outright did not want the child based on the variables reported above.
